   =20
      Hindenburg v. Icahn
   =20
 =20

Yesterday short seller Hindenburg Research=C2=A0released a short report on =
Carl Icahn=E2=80=99s company, Icahn Enterprises LP, and it is just mechanic=
ally very neat. Here is the schematic claim:
=09You have a company that is 85% owned by one guy. It owns $100 worth of s=
tuff.=09Every year it declares a 45% dividend, meaning that it pays out $45=
 of cash from its $100 worth of stuff.=09The main guy says =E2=80=9Cthat=E2=
=80=99s okay, no dividend for me, just give me my dividend in extra shares.=
=E2=80=9D Everyone else gets cash.=09That means the company only has to com=
e up with $6.75 of cash for that 30% dividend.=09The market is like =E2=80=
=9Cthis is amazing, this company has a huge dividend,=E2=80=9D and the stoc=
k trades up. It trades to a market capitalization of=C2=A0$300, three times=
 its net asset value, purely as a dividend investment. This gives it a 15% =
dividend yield, i.e., the $45 dividend divided by the $300 stock value is 1=
5%, making it one of the highest-yielding stocks available.=09The company t=
akes advantage of this fact to sell stock: It sells 2.25% of the company ($=
6.75=C2=A0worth of stock) to raise the money to pay out the $6.75 cash divi=
dend. (Implicitly it also sells $38.25 of stock to the main guy=C2=A0in lie=
u of=C2=A0his cash dividend, keeping=C2=A0his stake at 85%.
  [1]
)

That is, the two central claims here are that Icahn Enterprises is=C2=A0ove=
rvalued, relative to its reported net asset value, because investors are to=
o dazzled by its high dividend:

IEP trades at a 218% premium to its last reported net asset value (NAV), va=
stly higher than all comparables. =E2=80=A6
A reason for IEP=E2=80=99s extreme premium to NAV, based on a review of ret=
ail investor-oriented media, is that average investors are attracted to (a)=
 IEP=E2=80=99s large dividend yield and (b) the prospect of investing along=
side Wall Street legend Carl Icahn. Institutional investors have virtually =
no ownership in IEP.
Icahn Enterprises=E2=80=99 current dividend yield is ~15.8%, making it the =
highest dividend yield of any U.S. large cap company by far, with the next =
closest at ~9.9%.

And that the dividend is in some sense=C2=A0fake, because it comes not from=
 earnings but from selling new stock:

As a result of the company=E2=80=99s elevated unit price, its annual divide=
nd rate equates to an absurd 50.5% of last reported indicative net asset va=
lue.
The company=E2=80=99s outlier dividend is made possible (for now) because C=
arl Icahn owns roughly 85% of IEP and has been largely taking dividends in =
units (instead of cash), reducing the overall cash outlay required to meet =
the dividend payment for remaining unitholders.
The dividend is entirely unsupported by IEP=E2=80=99s cash flow and investm=
ent performance, which has been negative for years. IEP=E2=80=99s investmen=
t portfolio has lost ~53% since 2014. The company=E2=80=99s free cash flow =
figures show IEP has cumulatively burned ~$4.9 billion over the same period=
.

There are other claims, including that Icahn Enterprises overvalues some of=
 its assets in computing its net asset value, and that it makes bad investm=
ents and so has negative operating cash flow in a way that further shrinks =
the asset value and makes the dividend unsustainable, but those are less in=
teresting than the main schematic story. ( Icahn Enterprises responded: =E2=
=80=9CWe believe the self-serving short seller report published by=C2=A0Hin=
denburg Research=C2=A0today was intended solely to generate profits on Hind=
enburg's short position at the expense of IEP's long-term unitholders. We s=
tand by our public disclosures and we believe that IEP's performance will s=
peak for itself over the long term as it always has.=E2=80=9D)
That main story is ...=C2=A0what is that? Here=E2=80=99s what Hindenburg ca=
lls it:
In brief, Icahn has been using money taken in from new investors to pay out=
 dividends to old investors. Such ponzi-like economic structures are sustai=
nable only to the extent that new money is willing to risk being the last o=
ne =E2=80=9Cholding the bag=E2=80=9D.
Look, I personally do not view the term =E2=80=9Cponzi-like economic struct=
ure=E2=80=9D as a=C2=A0pejorative =E2=80=94=C2=A0many of my favorite econom=
ic structures are Ponzi-like =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=C2=A0agree that this schema=
tic structure seems Ponzi-like, but in a fun way.
Basically the accusation is that the shares trade for more than they are wo=
rth, so Icahn is selling more shares for more than they are worth in order =
to pay a big dividend to his shareholders. Which =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I think=C2=
=A0is simply correct corporate finance?=C2=A0If your shares are trading for=
 more than they are worth, you should sell as many shares as you can, and i=
f you don=E2=80=99t have any good use for the money you should use it to pa=
y a dividend.=C2=A0It is=C2=A0strange=C2=A0corporate finance, but it checks=
 out. Icahn Enterprises does disclose its indicative net asset value (thoug=
h Hindenburg quibbles with its calculations), so=C2=A0no one is exactly=C2=
=A0deceived=C2=A0here. If you buy the stock, you know. you=E2=80=99re payin=
g a=C2=A0huge premium to the net asset value.
But is it =E2=80=9Csustainable only to the extent that new money is willing=
 to risk being the last one =E2=80=98holding the bag=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D? I d=
on=E2=80=99t know. I think if you look at that schematic description, it se=
ems sustainable for a long time, even in the absence of new money (or inves=
ting gains or operating cash flow, ha), as long as Carl Icahn is willing to=
 risk being the last one holding the bag. The schematic description is some=
thing like: =E2=80=9CCarl Icahn is the majority owner of=C2=A0a bag of cash=
, and he keeps giving people some of the=C2=A0cash in exchange for an incre=
asing share of the smaller bag of cash.=E2=80=9D
If =E2=80=94=C2=A0using my schematic numbers above =E2=80=94=C2=A0the stock=
 fell from $300 (overvalued relative to the $100 of assets) to $50 (underva=
lued relative to the $100 of assets), the main guy might be perfectly happy=
 to keep paying out $6.75=C2=A0of cash dividends to outside shareholders in=
 order to increase his share of the now undervalued pot. If the shares trad=
ed for less than they were worth, Icahn Enterprises should stop selling sha=
res, but the dividend mechanism essentially lets Icahn=C2=A0buy=C2=A0shares=
: Everyone else gets a cash dividend,
  [2]
 but Icahn himself takes his dividend in stock, valued at its current tradi=
ng price,
  [3]
=C2=A0meaning that if the shares become cheap he is effectively buying shar=
es cheap. He gets an increasing share of a decreasing bag of cash, but his =
share increases faster than the bag shrinks.
  [4]
=C2=A0When your stock is overvalued, you sell stock; when your stock is und=
ervalued, you buy it back. Somehow Icahn is doing both!
Still in some sense the core of Hindenburg=E2=80=99s thesis is =E2=80=9Cthi=
s stock trades at a 218% premium to net asset value, which is weirdly high,=
=E2=80=9D and it=E2=80=99s hard to argue with that, though also a bit hard =
to see why the market never noticed it before.=C2=A0The stock closed at $50=
.42 on Monday; it was trading around $32.69 at noonish today. Still plenty =
of room to sell stock to fund dividends though.

