      People are worried about stock buybacks
   =20
 =20

There is an obvious, popular but not particularly good reason to be worried=
 about stock buybacks, which is something like =E2=80=9Ccompanies should no=
t spend their money on buying back their own stock, but on building factori=
es and paying higher salaries and researching new products and paying down =
debt and building up a cash reserve in case of disaster.=E2=80=9D
  [6]
=C2=A0This reason is probably true about some companies at some times, but =
as a general theory it sort of misunderstands corporate finance. The point =
of a company is to do some things that (1) it can do and (2) have positive =
expected value. Some companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0often in the early stages of =
their lives =E2=80=94=C2=A0have a lot of opportunities and not much cash, s=
o they sell shares to investors to raise cash to pursue opportunities. Many=
 other companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0often in the later stages of their lives =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0have a lot of cash (from previous successes) and dwindling o=
pportunities, so they give money back to the investors who funded them earl=
ier. It is implausible that a company would always have just enough cash fr=
om its previous operations to invest in valuable future projects. Sometimes=
 they have less money than opportunity and sell stock to raise money; other=
 times they have less opportunity than money and use money to buy back stoc=
k.
From the investor=E2=80=99s perspective, they buy stock from a company to b=
et that it will do good business, and then the company buys it back when th=
e bet pays off. If companies could never buy back stock, then the bets coul=
d never pay off.
  [7]
=C2=A0Why would you put money into a company if you could never get it back=
?
  [8]

And yet people=C2=A0are=C2=A0worried about stock buybacks, and there are so=
me sort of hipster reasons to worry about stock buybacks that don=E2=80=99t=
 suffer from this problem. One is that stock buybacks are a way to juice ex=
ecutive pay. The theory is something like: Executives get paid a lot in sto=
ck, which dilutes existing shareholders. Shareholders would be sad if they =
noticed this dilution, so companies spend shareholder money to buy back sto=
ck to minimize the dilution, which=C2=A0leads to executives being overpaid.
This theory also does not make very much sense =E2=80=94=C2=A0the stock-bas=
ed pay, and the buybacks, are public information, and the executive pay is =
set in some sort of market that seems imperfect, but surely not mainly beca=
use of stock buybacks. But you can refine it.
One refinement goes like this: Buybacks create an opportunity for executive=
s to=C2=A0sell=C2=A0stock at a profit. An executive owns stock, she wants s=
ome cash, she knows that if she just dumped her shares in the open market t=
he price would go down, so she makes her company announce a stock buyback, =
which pushes up the price (because it sends a bullish signal, and also just=
 because the company is buying shares and moving the price up). And then sh=
e sells her stock while the company is buying. Effectively, she sells stock=
=C2=A0into=C2=A0the buyback; she uses shareholder money to cash out her own=
 stock.=C2=A0
This theory (1) does seem bad, if true, (2) has some empirical support and =
(3) seems popular within the US Securities and Exchange Commission. In part=
icular, former SEC Commissioner Robert Jackson is a proponent of this theor=
y, and while he was at the SEC he did research supporting it. From  a 2018 =
speech:

We dove into the data, studying 385 buybacks over the last fifteen months. =
We matched those buybacks by hand to information on executive stock sales a=
vailable in SEC filings. First, we found that a buyback announcement leads =
to a big jump in stock price: in the 30 days after the announcements we stu=
died, firms enjoy abnormal returns of more than 2.5%. That=E2=80=99s unsurp=
rising: when a public company in the United States announces that it thinks=
 the stock is cheap, investors bid up its price.
What did surprise us, however, was how commonplace it is for executives to =
use buybacks as a chance to cash out. In half of the buybacks we studied, a=
t least one executive sold shares in the month following the buyback announ=
cement. In fact, twice as many companies have insiders selling in the eight=
 days after a buyback announcement as sell on an ordinary day. So right aft=
er the company tells the market that the stock is cheap, executives overwhe=
lmingly decide to sell.
And, in the process, executives take a lot of cash off the table. On averag=
e, in the days before a buyback announcement, executives trade in relativel=
y small amounts=E2=80=94less than $100,000 worth. But during the eight days=
 following a buyback announcement, executives on average sell more than $50=
0,000 worth of stock each day=E2=80=94a fivefold increase. Thus, executives=
 personally capture the benefit of the short-term stock-price pop created b=
y the buyback announcement.
Now, let=E2=80=99s be clear: this trading is not necessarily illegal. But i=
t is troubling, because it is yet another piece of evidence that executives=
 are spending more time on short-term stock trading than long-term value cr=
eation. It=E2=80=99s one thing for a corporate board and top executives to =
decide that a buyback is the right thing to do with the company=E2=80=99s c=
apital. It=E2=80=99s another for them to use that decision as an opportunit=
y to pocket some cash at the expense of the shareholders they have a duty t=
o protect, the workers they employ, or the communities they serve.

Today the SEC  adopted new rules on stock buybacks. The rules do three main=
 things. One is that they will require companies to disclose, at the end of=
 each quarter,=C2=A0daily=C2=A0information about how many shares they bough=
t each day of that quarter and at what prices. I suspect that most of the t=
ime this will be sort of voluminous and boring, but every so often it will =
be revealing. (If a company announced=C2=A0bad news one day in the middle o=
f a quarter, did it stop its stock buyback the day before the announcement?=
 A week before? If it did, that seems almost insider-trader-y; the company =
acted on the news before it announced it. If it didn=E2=80=99t, that seems =
dumb.)
Another thing that the rules will do is require companies to disclose, each=
 quarter, =E2=80=9Cthe objectives or rationales for its share repurchases a=
nd the process or criteria used to determine the amount of repurchases.=E2=
=80=9D This seems like a nod to the theory that stock buybacks are bad beca=
use companies should be using the money for better purposes instead: Compan=
ies will have to=C2=A0say=C2=A0something like =E2=80=9Cwe decided that a st=
ock buyback is a better use of our cash than other possible uses of cash,=
=E2=80=9D which is clarifying and perhaps embarrassing. Also, in US securit=
ies disclosure, it=E2=80=99s something to sue about. When these rules were =
first proposed in 2021,   I wrote:

=E2=80=9CThe objective or rationale for its share repurchases=E2=80=9D is g=
oing to get real formulaic real quick? Part of the point here is just to ma=
ke it a tiny bit more annoying for companies to buy back stock by making th=
em type this somewhat embarrassing formulaic declaration.
But part of the point is of course that everything is securities fraud. Now=
 companies will need to say, in their securities filings, that they are buy=
ing back stock for good reasons and not to enrich their executives. And now=
 disgruntled shareholders will be able to sue, saying =E2=80=9Cactually you=
 bought back stock to enrich your executives and lied about it in your secu=
rities filings.=E2=80=9D

Or, I mean, you write in the disclosure =E2=80=9Cwe decided to buy back sto=
ck at $50 because we thought the stock was undervalued,=E2=80=9D and then s=
omething bad happens and the stock falls to $40, and you get sued for sayin=
g it was undervalued at $50?
But a third thing that the rules will do is require disclosure about execut=
ives selling into the buyback: =E2=80=9CIssuers will also be required to in=
clude a checkbox indicating whether certain officers and directors traded i=
n the relevant securities in the four business days before or after the ann=
ouncement of the repurchase plan or program,=E2=80=9D and will have to disc=
lose =E2=80=9Cany policies and procedures relating to purchases and sales o=
f the issuer=E2=80=99s securities during a repurchase program by its office=
rs and directors, including any restriction on such transactions.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
In general, a lot of SEC rules are written in code, and in particular =E2=
=80=9Ccompanies will have to disclose any policies restricting X=E2=80=9D m=
eans =E2=80=9Ccompanies should not allow X=E2=80=9D: The SEC here is convey=
ing its preference that companies=C2=A0not allow their executives to sell i=
nto stock buybacks. In the fights over stock buybacks, this strikes me as k=
ind of a weird niche concern, but it=E2=80=99s the SEC=E2=80=99s weird nich=
e concern. If you think that stock buybacks are bad specifically because th=
ey give executives an opportunity to sell stock, then the simple solution i=
s to restrict executives from selling stock during stock buybacks, and that=
 is, sort of, what the SEC is doing here.

