<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday short seller Hindenburg Research=C2=
=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31366713.261431=
/aHR0cHM6Ly9oaW5kZW5idXJncmVzZWFyY2guY29tL2ljYWhuLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBeabfb7d4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">released a short report on Carl Icahn=E2=80=99s company=
</a>, Icahn Enterprises LP, and it is just mechanically very neat. Here is =
the schematic claim:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have a company that is 85% owned =
by one guy. It owns $100 worth of stuff.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">Every year it declares a 45% dividend, meaning that it pays out $45 =
of cash from its $100 worth of stuff.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">The main guy says =E2=80=9Cthat=E2=80=99s okay, no dividend for me, jus=
t give me my dividend in extra shares.=E2=80=9D Everyone else gets cash.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">That means the company only has to c=
ome up with $6.75 of cash for that 30% dividend.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">The market is like =E2=80=9Cthis is amazing, this company ha=
s a huge dividend,=E2=80=9D and the stock trades up. It trades to a market =
capitalization of=C2=A0$300, three times its net asset value, purely as a d=
ividend investment. This gives it a 15% dividend yield, i.e., the $45 divid=
end divided by the $300 stock value is 15%, making it one of the highest-yi=
elding stocks available.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The compa=
ny takes advantage of this fact to sell stock: It sells 2.25% of the compan=
y ($6.75=C2=A0worth of stock) to raise the money to pay out the $6.75 cash =
dividend. (Implicitly it also sells $38.25 of stock to the main guy=C2=A0<e=
m>in lieu of=C2=A0</em>his cash dividend, keeping=C2=A0<em>his </em>stake a=
t 85%.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>)</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, the two central claims here are that =
Icahn Enterprises is=C2=A0<em>overvalued</em>, relative to its reported net=
 asset value, because investors are too dazzled by its high dividend:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">IEP trades at a 218% premium to its last repor=
ted net asset value (NAV), vastly higher than all comparables. =E2=80=A6</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A reason for IEP=E2=80=99s extreme premium to =
NAV, based on a review of retail investor-oriented media, is that average i=
nvestors are attracted to (a) IEP=E2=80=99s large dividend yield and (b) th=
e prospect of investing alongside Wall Street legend Carl Icahn. Institutio=
nal investors have virtually no ownership in IEP.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Icahn Enterprises=E2=80=99 current dividend yi=
eld is ~15.8%, making it the highest dividend yield of any U.S. large cap c=
ompany by far, with the next closest at ~9.9%.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And that the dividend is in some sense=C2=A0<e=
m>fake</em>, because it comes not from earnings but from selling new stock:=
</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a result of the company=E2=80=99s elevated =
unit price, its annual dividend rate equates to an absurd 50.5% of last rep=
orted indicative net asset value.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company=E2=80=99s outlier dividend is made=
 possible (for now) because Carl Icahn owns roughly 85% of IEP and has been=
 largely taking dividends in units (instead of cash), reducing the overall =
cash outlay required to meet the dividend payment for remaining unitholders=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The dividend is entirely unsupported by IEP=E2=
=80=99s cash flow and investment performance, which has been negative for y=
ears. IEP=E2=80=99s investment portfolio has lost ~53% since 2014. The comp=
any=E2=80=99s free cash flow figures show IEP has cumulatively burned ~$4.9=
 billion over the same period.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are other claims, including that Icahn E=
nterprises overvalues some of its assets in computing its net asset value, =
and that it makes bad investments and so has negative operating cash flow i=
n a way that further shrinks the asset value and makes the dividend unsusta=
inable, but those are less interesting than the main schematic story. (<a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31366713.261431/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuaWVscC5jb20vbmV3cy1yZWxlYXNlcy9uZXdzLXJlbGVhc2UtZGV0YWlscy9pY2Fob=
i1lbnRlcnByaXNlcy1pc3N1ZXMtc3RhdGVtZW50LXJlZ2FyZGluZy1zaG9ydC1zZWxsZXItcmVw=
b3J0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBac5dc2f7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Icahn Enterprises responde=
d</a>: =E2=80=9CWe believe the self-serving short seller report published b=
y=C2=A0Hindenburg Research=C2=A0today was intended solely to generate profi=
ts on Hindenburg's short position at the expense of IEP's long-term unithol=
ders. We stand by our public disclosures and we believe that IEP's performa=
nce will speak for itself over the long term as it always has.=E2=80=9D)</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That main story is ...=C2=A0what is that? Here=
=E2=80=99s what Hindenburg calls it:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In brief, Icahn has been using mon=
ey taken in from new investors to pay out dividends to old investors. Such =
ponzi-like economic structures are sustainable only to the extent that new =
money is willing to risk being the last one =E2=80=9Cholding the bag=E2=80=
=9D.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look, I personally do not view the term =E2=80=
=9Cponzi-like economic structure=E2=80=9D as a=C2=A0<em>pejorative</em> =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0many of my favorite economic structures are Ponzi-like =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0and=C2=A0agree that this schematic structure seems Ponzi-like, but=
 in a fun way.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically the accusation is that the shares tr=
ade for more than they are worth, so Icahn is selling more shares for more =
than they are worth in order to pay a big dividend to his shareholders. Whi=
ch =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I think=C2=A0is simply correct corporate finance?=C2=A0If=
 your shares are trading for more than they are worth, you should sell as m=
any shares as you can, and if you don=E2=80=99t have any good use for the m=
oney you should use it to pay a dividend.=C2=A0It is=C2=A0<em>strange=C2=A0=
</em>corporate finance, but it checks out. Icahn Enterprises does disclose =
its indicative net asset value (though Hindenburg quibbles with its calcula=
tions), so=C2=A0no one is exactly=C2=A0<em>deceived</em>=C2=A0here. If you =
buy the stock, you know. you=E2=80=99re paying a=C2=A0huge premium to the n=
et asset value.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But is it =E2=80=9Csustainable only to the ext=
ent that new money is willing to risk being the last one =E2=80=98holding t=
he bag=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D? I don=E2=80=99t know. I think if you look at that=
 schematic description, it seems sustainable for a long time, even in the a=
bsence of new money (or investing gains or operating cash flow, ha), as lon=
g as <em>Carl Icahn</em> is willing to risk being the last one holding the =
bag. The schematic description is something like: =E2=80=9CCarl Icahn is th=
e majority owner of=C2=A0a bag of cash, and he keeps giving people some of =
the=C2=A0cash in exchange for an increasing share of the smaller bag of cas=
h.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If =E2=80=94=C2=A0using my schematic numbers a=
bove =E2=80=94=C2=A0the stock fell from $300 (overvalued relative to the $1=
00 of assets) to $50 (undervalued relative to the $100 of assets), the main=
 guy might be perfectly happy to keep paying out $6.75=C2=A0of cash dividen=
ds to outside shareholders in order to increase his share of the now <em>un=
dervalued</em> pot. If the shares traded for less than they were worth, Ica=
hn Enterprises should stop <em>selling</em> shares, but the dividend mechan=
ism essentially lets Icahn=C2=A0<em>buy=C2=A0</em>shares: Everyone else get=
s a cash dividend,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> but Icahn himself takes his dividend in stock, valued at its current t=
rading price,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0meaning that if the shares become cheap he is effectively buying =
shares cheap. He gets an increasing share of a decreasing bag of cash, but =
his share increases faster than the bag shrinks.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0When your stock is overvalued, you sell stock; when your stock is=
 undervalued, you buy it back. Somehow Icahn is doing both!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still in some sense the core of Hindenburg=E2=
=80=99s thesis is =E2=80=9Cthis stock trades at a 218% premium to net asset=
 value, which is weirdly high,=E2=80=9D and it=E2=80=99s hard to argue with=
 that, though also a bit hard to see why the market never noticed it before=
.=C2=A0The stock closed at $50.42 on Monday; it was trading around $32.69 a=
t noonish today. Still plenty of room to sell stock to fund dividends thoug=
h.</p>
