lick/31366713.261431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMjMtMDItMDEvYW1jLWhhcy1zb21lLWNsZXZlci1hcGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MDMyM19NT=
05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJt=
PTIzMDUwMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8d8154b=
6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> few times</a> about a problem that AMC Entertainment Holdings=
 Inc. has, and its clever solution. The problem is that AMC, a meme-stock c=
ompany, would like to sell bushels of stock to its enthusiastic retail shar=
eholders to raise money to buy gold mines or whatever, but it has already s=
old so much stock that it is out of authorized shares: Its corporate charte=
r only allows it to issue about 524 million shares, and it has sold pretty =
much all of them. It can amend the charter, but, under Delaware law, that r=
equires a majority vote of all of AMC=E2=80=99s shares, and for the most pa=
rt retail shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0even enthusiastic meme-stock retail s=
hareholders =E2=80=94 just don=E2=80=99t vote. So it can=E2=80=99t get enou=
gh votes to amend the charter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The solution was to issue a new class of stock=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0called APEs, AMC Preferred Equity units =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=
 votes with the common stock, to sell a lot of APEs to sympathetic hedge fu=
nds who will vote to amend the charter, and to make it so that the APEs, in=
 effect, automatically vote: If you own some APEs and don=E2=80=99t vote th=
em, your APEs are voted proportionally to how all the other APEs are voted.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC did this, it worked =E2=80=94=C2=A0it got,=
 by its own count, a majority of its shares to vote for the charter amendme=
nt=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but some shareholders sued and AMC is stuck in a bit=
 of a limbo. (It reached a settlement in the lawsuit, but some shareholders=
 objected to the settlement, and a Delaware judge is <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31366713.261431/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29t=
YmVyZ2xhdy5jb20vZXNnL2FtYy1qdWRnZS1zZXRzLWp1bmUtMjktc2V0dGxlbWVudC1oZWFyaW5=
nLXNpZ25hbHMtbm8tc2hvcnRjdXRz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4f434073" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 going to hear arguments next month</a>.) The claim in the lawsuit is basic=
ally that the APEs are a complicated trick to get around the voting require=
ments of Delaware law (which is true), and that this should not be allowed =
(which is debatable).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Delaware is where most US public companies are=
 incorporated. A <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
1366713.261431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MjMtMDItMTYvdGhlLXNlYy1jb21lcy1mb3ItY3J5cHRvLWN1c3RvZHk_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwMzI=
zX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3=
Rlcm09MjMwNTAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB131=
4899a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> number</a> of other <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/31366713.261431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMjgvYW1jLXMtYXBlcy1oYXZlLXRvLXdhaXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJE=
MDUwMzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXI=
mdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBa004ce50" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> companies</a> have had to deal with this problem of =
meme-stock governance recently, and have used similar approaches, issuing w=
eird preferred stocks with weird voting mechanics to deal with the problem =
of retail shareholders who don=E2=80=99t vote. It is <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31366713.261431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMTgvcHVycGxlLWR1bXBzLWl0cy1wcnB=
scz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTAzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2=
U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB665b066c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> not ideal</a>. On the one hand, thes=
e companies are probably=C2=A0<em>right</em>, as a matter of corporate fina=
nce, that they should issue more stock, and they are probably=C2=A0<em>righ=
t</em>, as a matter of responsiveness to their shareholders, that it is wha=
t a majority of their shareholders want. On the other hand, it is not a gre=
at precedent for Delaware courts to allow corporate directors to rig shareh=
older votes to get the results that they want: If you allow too much of thi=
s, then a company whose shareholders=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>want =
to do something will issue a lot of weird preferred stock to allied investo=
rs to get a different result.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But at least the AMC situation is really about=
 solving an inconvenience in Delaware law, which is that the law requires a=
 majority of all voting shares to approve an increase in the number of auth=
orized shares. If 39% of shareholders vote yes, 1% vote no and 60% don=E2=
=80=99t bother to vote, you can=E2=80=99t increase the number of shares, ev=
en though it seems clear that most of your shareholders want you to =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s just that a lot of them don=E2=80=99t vote. Fixing th=
is problem with weird preferred stock is clever, but has its own complicati=
ons. It might be better to fix it by=C2=A0<em>changing Delaware law=C2=A0</=
em>to make it more convenient for the meme-stock era.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a client <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/31366713.261431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmxmLmNvbS8yMDI=
zLXByb3Bvc2VkLWFtZW5kbWVudHMtdG8tdGhlLWdlbmVyYWwtY29ycG9yYXRpb24tbGF3LW9mLX=
RoZS1zdGF0ZS1vZi1kZWxhd2FyZS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbc88117f" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 memo from Richards, Layton &amp; Finger</a>, a leading Delaware law firm:<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Legislation proposing to amend the General Cor=
poration Law of the State of Delaware (the =E2=80=9CDGCL=E2=80=9D) is expec=
ted to be introduced to the Delaware General Assembly for consideration dur=
ing its 2023 regular session. =C2=A0If enacted, the 2023 amendments to the =
DGCL will, among other things, make the following changes: =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Section 242 will be revised to (i) eliminate t=
he need to obtain the default vote of stockholders for charter amendments e=
ffecting specified types of forward stock splits and associated increases i=
n the authorized number of shares, and (ii) reduce the minimum stockholder =
vote required to authorize a charter amendment increasing or decreasing the=
 authorized shares of a class, or effecting a reverse split of the shares o=
f a class, in circumstances where the shares of such class are listed on a =
national securities exchange immediately before the amendment becomes effec=
tive and meet the listing requirements of such exchange after the amendment=
 becomes effective.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, the law might be changed to fix the A=
PE problem. The memo goes on:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In recent years, due to a wider di=
spersion of shares among retail holders and policies in which brokerage fir=
ms decline to exercise their discretionary authority to vote shares held in=
 =E2=80=9Cstreet name,=E2=80=9D many public corporations have encountered s=
ignificant difficulty in securing various stockholder votes and, in particu=
lar, a vote necessary to effect a reverse stock split to help a corporation=
 maintain the minimum share price amount necessary to be listed on a nation=
al securities exchange. =C2=A0The lack of interest and participation among =
stockholders and beneficial owners in these critical votes is often attribu=
table not to the merits of the proposal=E2=80=94few stockholders, it would =
seem, would support a de-listing that would assuredly diminish the liquidit=
y of the stock=E2=80=94but to =E2=80=9Crational apathy=E2=80=9D among retai=
l and other dispersed investors, each of whom individually owns too few sha=
res to have a vested interest in the corporation but all of whom collective=
ly represent a significant portion of the voting base. =C2=A0New Section 24=
2(d)(2) provides that a corporation may amend its certificate of incorporat=
ion to increase or decrease the authorized shares of a class of stock, or t=
o effect a reverse stock split in respect of a class of stock, without obta=
ining the vote or votes otherwise required by Section 242(b) (i.e., at leas=
t a majority in voting power of the outstanding stock entitled to vote ther=
eon) if (i) the shares ... are listed on a national exchange =E2=80=A6, (ii=
) at a meeting of stockholders at which a vote is taken for and against the=
 proposed amendment, the votes cast for the amendment exceed the votes cast=
 against the amendment, and (iii) the amendment increases or decreases the =
number of shares of a class of stock that has not opted out of the class vo=
te. ...=C2=A0 As new Section 242(d)(2) refers only to votes cast for or aga=
inst an amendment, it makes clear that abstentions have no effect on whethe=
r the required approval is obtained. =C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This seems like a rational change in the law f=
or the meme-stock era, and a better solution than the APE stuff.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile the APE lawsuit is still ongoing, an=
d I=E2=80=99m not sure which way this cuts? On the one hand, the new law, i=
f adopted, suggests that AMC was right to identify a problem and fix it; it=
=E2=80=99s hard to say that AMC shouldn=E2=80=99t have gotten around the sh=
areholder voting requirement when the Delaware legislature now agrees that =
the requirement was too strict. On the other hand, if there is going to be=
=C2=A0a legislative fix, you kind of don=E2=80=99t need the clunky APE mech=
anic anymore, which might make a judge less inclined to approve it.</p>
