<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is an obvious, popular but not particula=
rly good reason to be worried about stock buybacks, which is something like=
 =E2=80=9Ccompanies should not spend their money on buying back their own s=
tock, but on building factories and paying higher salaries and researching =
new products and paying down debt and building up a cash reserve in case of=
 disaster.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0This reason is probably true about some companies at some times, =
but as a general theory it sort of misunderstands corporate finance. The po=
int of a company is to do some things that (1) it can do and (2) have posit=
ive expected value. Some companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0often in the early stages=
 of their lives =E2=80=94=C2=A0have a lot of opportunities and not much cas=
h, so they sell shares to investors to raise cash to pursue opportunities. =
Many other companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0often in the later stages of their live=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0have a lot of cash (from previous successes) and dwindling=
 opportunities, so they give money back to the investors who funded them ea=
rlier. It is implausible that a company would always have just enough cash =
from its previous operations to invest in valuable future projects. Sometim=
es they have less money than opportunity and sell stock to raise money; oth=
er times they have less opportunity than money and use money to buy back st=
ock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From the investor=E2=80=99s perspective, they =
buy stock from a company to bet that it will do good business, and then the=
 company buys it back when the bet pays off. If companies could never buy b=
ack stock, then the bets could never pay off.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Why would you put money into a company if you could never get it =
back?<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: =
transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And yet people=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>worried =
about stock buybacks, and there are some sort of hipster reasons to worry a=
bout stock buybacks that don=E2=80=99t suffer from this problem. One is tha=
t stock buybacks are a way to juice executive pay. The theory is something =
like: Executives get paid a lot in stock, which dilutes existing shareholde=
rs. Shareholders would be sad if they noticed this dilution, so companies s=
pend shareholder money to buy back stock to minimize the dilution, which=C2=
=A0leads to executives being overpaid.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This theory also does not make very much sense=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0the stock-based pay, and the buybacks, are public informati=
on, and the executive pay is set in some sort of market that seems imperfec=
t, but surely not mainly because of stock buybacks. But you can refine it.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One refinement goes like this: Buybacks create=
 an opportunity for executives to=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em>stock at a profit=
. An executive owns stock, she wants some cash, she knows that if she just =
dumped her shares in the open market the price would go down, so she makes =
her company announce a stock buyback, which pushes up the price (because it=
 sends a bullish signal, and also just because the company is buying shares=
 and moving the price up). And then she sells her stock while the company i=
s buying. Effectively, she sells stock=C2=A0<em>into=C2=A0</em>the buyback;=
 she uses shareholder money to cash out her own stock.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This theory (1) does seem bad, if true, (2) ha=
s some empirical support and (3) seems popular within the US Securities and=
 Exchange Commission. In particular, former SEC Commissioner Robert Jackson=
 is a proponent of this theory, and while he was at the SEC he did research=
 supporting it. From <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/31366713.261431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3NwZWVjaC9zcGVlY2gtamFj=
a3Nvbi0wNjExMTg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe9eeb930" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a 2018 speech</=
a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We dove into the data, studying 385 buybacks o=
ver the last fifteen months. We matched those buybacks by hand to informati=
on on executive stock sales available in SEC filings. First, we found that =
a buyback announcement leads to a big jump in stock price: in the 30 days a=
fter the announcements we studied, firms enjoy abnormal returns of more tha=
n 2.5%. That=E2=80=99s unsurprising: when a public company in the United St=
ates announces that it thinks the stock is cheap, investors bid up its pric=
e.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What did surprise us, however, was how commonp=
lace it is for executives to use buybacks as a chance to cash out. In half =
of the buybacks we studied, at least one executive sold shares in the month=
 following the buyback announcement. In fact, twice as many companies have =
insiders selling in the eight days after a buyback announcement as sell on =
an ordinary day. So right after the company tells the market that the stock=
 is cheap, executives overwhelmingly decide to sell.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, in the process, executives take a lot of =
cash off the table. On average, in the days before a buyback announcement, =
executives trade in relatively small amounts=E2=80=94less than $100,000 wor=
th. But during the eight days following a buyback announcement, executives =
on average sell more than $500,000 worth of stock each day=E2=80=94a fivefo=
ld increase. Thus, executives personally capture the benefit of the short-t=
erm stock-price pop created by the buyback announcement.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, let=E2=80=99s be clear: this trading is n=
ot necessarily illegal. But it is troubling, because it is yet another piec=
e of evidence that executives are spending more time on short-term stock tr=
ading than long-term value creation. It=E2=80=99s one thing for a corporate=
 board and top executives to decide that a buyback is the right thing to do=
 with the company=E2=80=99s capital. It=E2=80=99s another for them to use t=
hat decision as an opportunity to pocket some cash at the expense of the sh=
areholders they have a duty to protect, the workers they employ, or the com=
munities they serve.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today the SEC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/31366713.261431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3=
ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy04NQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBab104d46" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> ad=
opted new rules</a> on stock buybacks. The rules do three main things. One =
is that they will require companies to disclose, at the end of each quarter=
,=C2=A0<em>daily=C2=A0</em>information about how many shares they bought ea=
ch day of that quarter and at what prices. I suspect that most of the time =
this will be sort of voluminous and boring, but every so often it will be r=
evealing. (If a company announced=C2=A0bad news one day in the middle of a =
quarter, did it stop its stock buyback the day before the announcement? A w=
eek before? If it did, that seems almost insider-trader-y; the company acte=
d on the news before it announced it. If it didn=E2=80=99t, that seems dumb=
.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another thing that the rules will do is requir=
e companies to disclose, each quarter, =E2=80=9Cthe objectives or rationale=
s for its share repurchases and the process or criteria used to determine t=
he amount of repurchases.=E2=80=9D This seems like a nod to the theory that=
 stock buybacks are bad because companies should be using the money for bet=
ter purposes instead: Companies will have to=C2=A0<em>say=C2=A0</em>somethi=
ng like =E2=80=9Cwe decided that a stock buyback is a better use of our cas=
h than other possible uses of cash,=E2=80=9D which is clarifying and perhap=
s embarrassing. Also, in US securities disclosure, it=E2=80=99s something t=
o sue about. When these rules were first proposed in 2021, <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31366713.261431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMTYvdGhlLXNlYy1oYXMtYmlnL=
XBsYW5zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MDMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nv=
dXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUwMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd08cdac4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  I wrote</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe objective or rationale for its sh=
are repurchases=E2=80=9D is going to get real formulaic real quick? Part of=
 the point here is just to make it a tiny bit more annoying for companies t=
o buy back stock by making them type this somewhat embarrassing formulaic d=
eclaration.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But part of the point is of course that everyt=
hing is securities fraud. Now companies will need to say, in their securiti=
es filings, that they are buying back stock for good reasons and not to enr=
ich their executives. And now disgruntled shareholders will be able to sue,=
 saying =E2=80=9Cactually you bought back stock to enrich your executives a=
nd lied about it in your securities filings.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or, I mean, you write in the disclosure =E2=80=
=9Cwe decided to buy back stock at $50 because we thought the stock was und=
ervalued,=E2=80=9D and then something bad happens and the stock falls to $4=
0, and you get sued for saying it was undervalued at $50?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But a third thing that the rules will do is re=
quire disclosure about executives selling into the buyback: =E2=80=9CIssuer=
s will also be required to include a checkbox indicating whether certain of=
ficers and directors traded in the relevant securities in the four business=
 days before or after the announcement of the repurchase plan or program,=
=E2=80=9D and will have to disclose =E2=80=9Cany policies and procedures re=
lating to purchases and sales of the issuer=E2=80=99s securities during a r=
epurchase program by its officers and directors, including any restriction =
on such transactions.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In general, a lot of SEC rules are written in =
code, and in particular =E2=80=9Ccompanies will have to disclose any polici=
es restricting X=E2=80=9D means =E2=80=9Ccompanies should not allow X=E2=80=
=9D: The SEC here is conveying its preference that companies=C2=A0<em>not a=
llow their executives to sell into stock buybacks. </em>In the fights over =
stock buybacks, this strikes me as kind of a weird niche concern, but it=E2=
=80=99s the SEC=E2=80=99s weird niche concern. If you think that stock buyb=
acks are bad specifically because they give executives an opportunity to se=
ll stock, then the simple solution is to restrict executives from selling s=
tock during stock buybacks, and that is, sort of, what the SEC is doing her=
e.</p>
