ment date.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-4" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[4] <em>Again using the math from footnote 1. =
Say that the main shareholder owns 85 shares and everyone else owns 15. Net=
 asset value is $100 ($1 per share) and the market cap is $50 ($0.50 per sh=
are) because the stock price has fallen. The company declares a dividend of=
 $45 again, for a whopping 90% dividend yield. The main shareholder takes h=
is dividend in shares ($38.25 of shares); everyone else gets it in cash ($6=
.75 of cash). The main shareholder gets an extra 76.5 shares ($38.25 divide=
d by $0.50 share price), giving him a total of 161.5 shares; the other shar=
eholders keep their 15 shares. No new shares are sold. The main shareholder=
 now owns 91.5% of the pot, which has a value of $93.25 ($100 minus the $6.=
75 cash dividend); this makes his stake worth $85.33, up from $85 before th=
e dividend. (This does not always work; if the shares are only slightly und=
ervalued he ends up a net loser.)</em></p>
</div>
